                <head>No. 80.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Frelinghuysen</persName> to Mr.
                            <persName type="to">Young</persName>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1882-07-03">
                            <hi rend="italic">July</hi> 3, 1882</date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 17.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Mr. Holcombe’s dispatch of the 6th of May last,
                    in relation to the residence of American missionaries in the interior of China,
                    has been received. His exposition of the rights of citizens of the United States
                    in China in the note which he addressed to Mr. Carrow, on that date, is regarded
                    as a very clear and discreet statement of what may properly be claimed under the
                    stipulations of existing treaties for our citizens, residents in China, whether
                    engaged in the calling of missionaries or in any other pursuit, and meets with
                    the unqualified approval of the department.</p>
                <p>I am, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>FRED’K T. FRELINGHUYSEN.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
